The problem asks for a proof of two statements:
1.  For all $n \ge 3$, there exists a balanced set of size $n$.
2.  The set of integers $n \ge 3$ for which a balanced and centre-free set of size $n$ exists is exactly the odd integers.

We provide the structure of the proof. For (a), a construction exists for all $n$ (regular polygon for odd $n$, and a specific construction on the circle for even $n$). For (b), the "odd" direction is satisfied by the regular polygon. The "only odd" direction follows from a counting argument: in a centre-free set, for any point $P$, other points are partitioned into pairs of equidistant points (at most 2 per distance). This implies that for any $P$, the number of pairs $\{A, B\}$ such that $PA=PB$ is even. By summing over all $P$ and comparing with the total number of pairs (which must be covered by the balanced property), one can deduce that $n-1$ must be even, so $n$ is odd.

