The problem asks for two parts: establishing the existence of a balanced set for all $n \ge 3$, and identifying that balanced and centre-free sets exist precisely for odd $n \ge 3$.

For part (a), if $n$ is odd, a regular $n$-gon works. If $n$ is even, we can construct a set consisting of the center of a circle and $n-1$ points on the circle, arranged such that they form a disjoint union of an equilateral triangle (if needed) and pairs of points separated by $60^\circ$ (distance equals radius). This ensures every pair is balanced.

For part (b), if $n$ is odd, the regular $n$-gon is also centre-free. If $n$ is even, a counting argument on the number of pairs shows that a balanced centre-free set cannot exist. Specifically, for a centre-free set, each point $C$ can balance at most $\lfloor \frac{n-1}{2} \rfloor$ pairs. Summing over all $n$ points, the total capacity to balance pairs is $n \lfloor \frac{n-1}{2} \rfloor$. The total number of pairs is $\binom{n}{2}$. For even $n$, $\binom{n}{2} > n \lfloor \frac{n-1}{2} \rfloor$, yielding a contradiction.

