Consider the problem of constructing balanced sets and the constraint on center-free sets.

For part (a), we construct a "Fan" set. Let $O$ be the origin. We place $n-1$ points on the unit circle such that every point has at least one neighbor at distance 1 (which corresponds to an angle of $\pi/3$).
If $n-1$ is even, we form $(n-1)/2$ pairs of points with angle $\pi/3$.
If $n-1$ is odd, we form one triplet with angles $0, \pi/3, 2\pi/3$ and $(n-4)/2$ pairs.
This ensures every point on the circle is at distance 1 from another point on the circle.
The set $S = \{O\} \cup \text{points}$ is balanced:
- For two points on the circle, their bisector passes through $O$ (equidistant).
- For $O$ and a point $P$ on the circle, there exists a neighbor $Q$ on the circle with $dist(P, Q) = 1 = dist(O, Q)$.
Thus (a) is satisfied for all $n \ge 3$.

For part (b), we first show that if $n$ is even, no balanced center-free set exists.
Suppose $S$ is such a set with $|S|=n$. For each $P \in S$, let $M_P = \{\{A, B\} \subseteq S \mid A \ne B \land dist(P, A) = dist(P, B)\}$.
Since $S$ is center-free, no three points are equidistant from $P$, so the pairs in $M_P$ are disjoint. Thus $M_P$ is a matching in $S \setminus \{P\}$.
The size $|M_P| \le \lfloor (n-1)/2 \rfloor = (n-2)/2$ (since $n$ is even).
The condition that $S$ is balanced implies that every pair $\{A, B\}$ is in some $M_P$.
Summing over $P$, the total capacity is $\sum |M_P| \le n(n-2)/2$.
The total number of pairs is $\binom{n}{2} = n(n-1)/2$.
Since $n(n-2)/2 < n(n-1)/2$, this is a contradiction.
Thus $n$ must be odd.
Conversely, for $n$ odd, a regular $n$-gon is balanced (by symmetry) and center-free (circumcenter is origin, not in set).

