The proof involves two parts: showing the existence of a balanced set for all $n \ge 3$, and characterizing the integers $n$ for which a balanced centre-free set exists.

For part (a), we construct a balanced set for any $n \ge 3$.
If $n$ is odd, the vertices of a regular $n$-gon form a balanced set. The perpendicular bisector of any two vertices passes through a unique third vertex (the vertex opposite to the midpoint of the chord).
If $n$ is even, we construct a set of size $n$ by taking the origin $O$ and $n-1$ points on the unit circle. Since $n-1$ is odd, we can partition $n-1$ into disjoint sets of size 2 or 3, where each set forms a "chain" with distance equal to the radius $R=1$. Specifically, a pair $\{A, B\}$ with angular separation $\pi/3$ satisfies $dist(A,B)=1$. A triplet $\{A, B, C\}$ with consecutive separations $\pi/3$ satisfies $dist(A,B)=1, dist(B,C)=1$. We can arrange these components on the circle. For any pair on the circle, $O$ is equidistant. For any pair $(O, X)$, $X$ belongs to a component and has a neighbor $Y$ with $dist(X,Y)=1=dist(O,Y)$, so $Y$ balances $(O, X)$.

For part (b), we show that a balanced centre-free set must have odd cardinality.
Let $S$ be a balanced centre-free set of size $n$.
For any $P \in S$, the condition "centre-free" implies that no three points are equidistant from $P$. Thus, for any $r > 0$, there are at most 2 points at distance $r$ from $P$. Since $dist(P,P)=0$ is unique, the points $S \setminus \{P\}$ can be partitioned into pairs $\{A, B\}$ such that $dist(P,A)=dist(P,B)$.
This implies $n-1$ is even, so $n$ is odd.
Conversely, for odd $n$, the regular $n$-gon is balanced and centre-free (as the circumcenter is the origin, which is not in the set).

